													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>My impression is that they&#8217;ve been knocked over by sheer scale. How many web sites, after all, <i>start out</i> by registering millions of users? There are also rumors of DDoS attacks; who knows if the they are true.</p>
<p>The other day I was thinking that if you wanted an easy way to register this many users, you could much worse than to implement a Facebook app, or make it a Google service. Perhaps have a healthcare exchange API? Though it would have to be carefully secured.</p>
<p>And, as Jon Walker at FDL reminds us, Oregon&#8217;s Medicaid system has had no problem registering 56,000 new users. There is likewise little doubt that Medicare&#8217;s established systems could easily accommodate large numbers of additional users. This is a graphic demonstration that the privatization of the system itself adds expense and complexity.</p>
</div>

